{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-tsx","path":"/texts/tipitaka/sutta-pitaka/anguttara-nikaya/AN4/32-sangahasutta/","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>“Mendicants, there are these four ways of being inclusive.\nWhat four?\nGiving, kindly words, taking care, and equality. </p>\n<p>These are the four ways of being inclusive. </p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Giving and kindly words, <br>\ntaking care here, <br>\nand equality in worldly conditions, <br>\nin each case as they deserve. <br>\nThese ways of being inclusive in the world <br>\nare like a moving chariot’s linchpin. </p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If there were no such ways of being inclusive, <br>\nneither mother nor father <br>\nwould be respected and honored <br>\nfor what they’ve done for their children. </p>\n</blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>But since these ways of being inclusive do exist, <br>\nthe astute do regard them well, <br>\nso they achieve greatness <br>\nand are praised.” </p>\n</blockquote>\n<div style=\"text-align:center\">\n<p><a href=\"/texts/tipitaka/sutta-pitaka/anguttara-nikaya/AN4/33-sihasutta/\">AN.4.33. Sīhasutta (“The Lion”)</a></p>\n</div>","htmlAst":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"“Mendicants, there are these four ways of being inclusive.\nWhat four?\nGiving, kindly words, taking care, and equality. "}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"These are the four ways of being inclusive. "}]},{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"blockquote","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"\n"},{"type":"element","tagName":"p","properties":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Giving and kindly words, "},{"type":"element","tagName":"br","properties":{},"children":[]},{"type":"text","value":"\ntaking care here, "},{"type":"element","tagName":"br","properties":{},"children":[]},{"type":"t